09/Jan/12 10:05 AM;mxia;Trying to reduce it to the simplest snippet, so for the following code:

{code}
f.add()

// comments
{code}

the parser returns the following structure:

{code}
JSParseRootNode (0,19)
|_JSInvokeNode (0,19)
  |_ ...
{code}

Note the end offset of JSInvokeNode incorrectly includes the comment. If a semicolon is added to the first line (i.e "f.add();"), the parser will correctly return the right ending offset of 7 for JSInvokeNode.

Kevin, believe you are better suited to take a look at this issue than me.  I'm thinking because the comments are skipped in the token scanner for the parser, when the basic recovery strategy kicks in to add a semicolon, it adds to the end of the comments instead, and that's causing the problem.

